  Are homeless people being moved on to make way for Super Bowl 506 days agoOptions to share this contentWhatsAppFacebookTwitterShareShare this post onClose the expanded menuPinterestTumblrRedditCopy this linkRead more about these linksThe best part of North America is currently emptying chips into bowls Super Bowls if you will and enjoying a cold brew for chips and brew read crisps and beer Weird like that arent they as it warms up for perhaps the most grandiose sporting event of the year  Super Bowl 50As with all of these things the Super Bowl is a great chance for fans to get together and watch their favourite stars go head to head and its also a great chance for companies to well sell stuffThe list of official partners is impressive and those lucky enough to attend can enjoy the spectacle witha Bud Light the official beer sponsorof Super Bowl 50 we assume its what athletes drink  for the measly sum of 8 8 aglassthat is The 2015 game was watched by 114 million Americans and is the ultimate celebration of western consumer culture with a 30 second advertising slot during the game going for around 5 millionThats a lot of spendoolies Good job its all going back into developing the pockets of local peopleright Er maybes not Whilst Santa Clara  the city hosting the event looks to be getting reimbursed by the Host Committee for extra costs it seems that neighbours San Fran may not be getting any such help for the 5m or so theyre having to stump upTo compound matters there is unrest from locals who feel that in order to present a more agreeable picture to touristsorganisers and local officials are trying to socially cleanse the area Protesters took to the streets this week to object that Super Bowl city is leading to homeless locals being moved onAs Americas yearly festival of sporting pageantry makes rumbles into the Bay Area people are being told to clear outStu Woo of The Wall Street Journal writestwodozen people were essentially bumped to the top of a waiting list at San Franciscos most soughtafter shelterNow we know what youre thinking readers  now then BBC Three surely two dozen homeless San Franciscans getting bumped to the top of a waiting list on San Franciscos most soughtafter shelter is no bad thing  at least for said San Franciscans and you may be right but as Woo points out the knockon effect of this is that others who have been on the waiting list longer will lose outHipHop journalist who knew that was a job heyand activist Davey D has lent another angry voice in the protest against Super Bowl City describing the militarisation of the city with tourists taking selfies with armed police as well asa general sense of creeping gentrification99 percent of them will not be going to the Super Bowl because they cant afford the tickets even if its in their backyardMeanwhile no contrition from Mayor EdLee Hes come out to declare that those camped near the Super Bowl City site are going to have to leave and has shown his willingness to move them along forcibly with the aid of law enforcement in the months building up to the event citing public safety concerns for both fans and for the homelessIts estimated that it costs around 40500 a yearto house and care for one homeless person with severe mental illness which means roughly that the money accrued from just one of those 30 second ad spots during the Super Bowl could equate to housing and caring for 123 people who suffer that way You may call that crude economics but its a fairly stark comparisonAll in all if true this social cleanup paints apretty bleak picture The Super Bowl will undoubtedly bring millions of Americans together as big sporting occasions like this always do but there will also be those who feel like its just not for themStory comes from Joe Forrester ofThe BBC Three Playground


  
